µF2µJCThe evolution of the illegal Amiga scene. An interview with Hamster of TRSI.

µF1µC2by Lars "Ghandy" Sobiraj of Nukleus
	
µC0µF0µJLHow did the illegal cracker scene develop more than 30 years ago? In 1990, some years after it started, the origin of the cracked Amiga games were the bulletin board systems (BBSs) of the crews. From the ones like the Westpoint BBS from Hamster of TRSI, with whom we recently spoke at length.

µJLµF1Before the stuff was distributed by telephone lines, the mailswappers of the groups have sent the latest cracks across Europe as letters. But that was much slower, of course.

Back then, cracked software was also exchanged among friends or in the schoolyard. But as long as the crack was hot, the release groups distributed them in their own bulletin board systems. 30 years ago, the internet did not yet play a role in Germany. We interviewed Heinz-Willi Lietzow aka µC2HamsterµC0 from Düsseldorf, a former operator of such an illegal BBS (mailbox), in detail. We wanted to know how technical developments have affected the illegal scene when he was active. Hamster is still in business, organising the members of µC2TRSIµC0. They nowadays mostly create demo related stuff for various computer platforms.

The conversation was originally recorded for the website µC7tarnkappe.infoµC0 in the form of a podcast and transcribed some months later. We had to skip a lot of content, because the interview was getting far too long. If you want to hear it all in the german language, you can listen or download the podcast here: 

